result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (4th) [Modifiers: Alcohol Fine Enhancer] and Operating w/ PAC (4th) [Modifiers: Alcohol Fine Enhancer]. The defendant was found guilty of OWI (4th) [Modifiers: Alcohol Fine Enhancer] and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (4th) [Modifiers: Alcohol Fine Enhancer] was dismissed by the court.

  • Gene L Jenson was found guilty of OWI (4th) [Modifiers: Alcohol Fine Enhancer], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Bryan C. Bayer appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Defendant Gene L Jenson in court, in custody (Waukesha County Jail), with attorney Samuel W. Benedict. 
Motion filed by the Defense - Challenging Prior Convictions (OWI 2nd and OWI 3rd  out of Juneau County - Defendant did not waive his rights to an attorney on those two convictions).

Witness Called:  Gene Jenson (Defendant).
Witness Sworn and Testified.

Exhibits Marked: 1 - 3.
Exhibits 1 - 3 are offered and received.

Testimony Deemed Closed.
Defense presented closing arguments.
State presented closing arguments.
Response and replies presented.

Court finds/orders the following:  Reasons placed on the record.
Court finds there is an affirmative obligation by the court to conduct a colloquy with the defendant.
Court finds there was colloquy with the defendant as to the OWI 3rd and he did waive his rights.
However, court finds as to the OWI 2nd there is nothing in the record showing there was any colloquy given by the court (nothing addressing what the rights are that the defendant is waiving).
Court finds there is nothing in this record that the defendant affirmatively gave up his right as to an attorney or a trial as it relates to the OWI 2nd Juneau County Case 1996CT64.
Record from 1996 is deficient.
Therefore, the court finds the 1996 case can not be used as a predicate offense.
However, the court will give the State 2 weeks to supplement the record.
Matter continued to see if the State can supplement the record.
